---
import PageShell from '../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const title = "Insurance for International Pilots | Compare Expat Plans";
const description = "Health insurance guide for Pilots working internationally, covering aviation careers abroad, airline positions, and global flight operations.";
const headline = "Insurance for International Pilots";
const subheadline = "Coverage solutions for Pilots working abroad, flying internationally, and pursuing careers across airlines, charter operations, and aviation organizations worldwide.";
const canonicalPath = "/guides/pilot-insurance";
const heroBackgroundImage = "/images/guides/pilot-insurance-hero.png";

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'overview', label: 'Overview' },
  { id: 'coverage-needs', label: 'Coverage Needs' },
  { id: 'work-settings', label: 'Work Settings' },
  { id: 'credentials', label: 'Credentials' },
  { id: 'occupational-health', label: 'Occupational Health' },
  { id: 'work-demands', label: 'Work Demands' },
  { id: 'career-considerations', label: 'Career Considerations' },
  { id: 'faqs', label: 'FAQs' },
  { id: 'next-steps', label: 'Next Steps' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title={title}
  description={description}
  headline={headline}
  subheadline={subheadline}
  canonicalPath={canonicalPath}
  heroBackgroundImage={heroBackgroundImage}
  tocItems={tocItems}
>
  <article class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">

    <section id="overview">
      <h2>International Pilot Careers</h2>
      <p>
        Pilots operate aircraft for commercial airlines, charter companies, cargo operations, and private aviation. International pilot careers involve flying routes across multiple countries, relocating to foreign bases, or working for airlines headquartered outside your home country.
      </p>
      <p>
        International aviation opportunities exist through global airlines, regional carriers expanding operations, cargo carriers with worldwide networks, and private aviation companies serving international clients with complex travel needs.
      </p>
      <p>
        This guide addresses insurance considerations for Pilots working abroad across airlines, charter operations, and aviation organizations worldwide.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="coverage-needs">
      <h2>Coverage Needs for Pilots</h2>

      <ComparisonTable
        columns={[
          { key: 'need', header: 'Coverage Need' },
          { key: 'why', header: 'Why It Matters' },
          { key: 'typical', header: 'Coverage Situation?' },
        ]}
        rows={[
          { need: 'General health coverage', why: 'Professional health maintenance', typical: 'Usually airline-provided' },
          { need: 'Medical certificate support', why: 'Career depends on medical status', typical: 'Critical for pilots' },
          { need: 'Mental health support', why: 'Stress and sleep disruption', typical: 'Important to include' },
          { need: 'Vision and hearing', why: 'Required for medical certificate', typical: 'Essential coverage' },
          { need: 'Loss of license', why: 'Medical grounding protection', typical: 'Consider separately' },
          { need: 'Disability coverage', why: 'Career protection', typical: 'Important consideration' },
        ]}
      />

      <h3>Medical Certificate Dependency</h3>
      <p>
        Pilot careers depend entirely on maintaining a valid medical certificate. Any health condition that could affect flight safety—cardiovascular, neurological, psychiatric, or sensory—can result in medical grounding. Coverage that supports maintaining medical certification is essential.
      </p>
      <p>
        Loss of medical certificate means loss of career income. While separate loss of license insurance exists, health coverage should ideally support preventive care and early intervention to maintain flight fitness.
      </p>

      <h3>Circadian Disruption</h3>
      <p>
        Long-haul flying involves constant time zone changes and irregular sleep schedules. Circadian disruption affects physical health, mental wellbeing, and immune function. Health coverage should accommodate conditions exacerbated by pilot lifestyle demands.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="work-settings">
      <h2>Coverage by Work Setting</h2>

      <h3>Major Airlines</h3>
      <p>
        Flag carriers and major international airlines. Comprehensive benefits packages. Union representation. Major airlines offer stability and benefits.
      </p>

      <h3>Regional Airlines</h3>
      <p>
        Smaller carriers feeding major airlines. Benefits less comprehensive. Career progression stepping stone. Regionals offer experience building.
      </p>

      <h3>Cargo Airlines</h3>
      <p>
        Freight carriers worldwide. Good compensation often. Night operations common. Cargo offers lifestyle flexibility.
      </p>

      <h3>Charter Operations</h3>
      <p>
        Private and charter aviation. Benefits vary significantly. Varied flying. Charter offers flexibility.
      </p>

      <h3>Corporate Aviation</h3>
      <p>
        Private company flight departments. Benefits depend on company. Personalized service. Corporate offers predictability.
      </p>
    </section>

    <CTABox
      title="Coverage for Pilots"
      description="Compare international health plans designed for Pilots working abroad across airlines, charter operations, and aviation organizations worldwide."
      buttonText="Compare Pilot Plans"
      buttonHref="/"
      variant="highlight"
    />

    <section id="credentials">
      <h2>Credentials and Professional Recognition</h2>

      <h3>ATP License</h3>
      <p>
        Airline Transport Pilot certificate. Highest pilot credential. Required for airline captain. ATP enables career.
      </p>

      <h3>Type Ratings</h3>
      <p>
        Aircraft-specific certifications. Required for each aircraft type. Employer typically provides. Ratings expand opportunity.
      </p>

      <h3>Medical Certificate</h3>
      <p>
        First class medical required for ATP. Regular medical examinations. Career depends on medical status. Medical enables flying.
      </p>

      <h3>License Validation</h3>
      <p>
        Foreign license recognition. Process varies by country. May require conversion. Research destination requirements.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="occupational-health">
      <h2>Occupational Health Considerations</h2>

      <h3>Sleep Disruption</h3>
      <p>
        Irregular schedules. Time zone changes. Circadian rhythm disruption. Sleep impacts health and safety.
      </p>

      <h3>Radiation Exposure</h3>
      <p>
        Cosmic radiation at altitude. Long-term career exposure. Cumulative effects. Exposure monitoring valuable.
      </p>

      <h3>Cardiovascular</h3>
      <p>
        Sedentary cockpit time. Lifestyle factors. Career-ending if issues develop. Preventive care important.
      </p>

      <h3>Mental Health</h3>
      <p>
        Isolation and pressure. Family separation. Stress management. Mental health support valuable.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="work-demands">
      <h2>Managing Work Demands</h2>

      <h3>Flight Operations</h3>
      <p>
        Safe aircraft operation. Crew coordination. Passenger responsibility. Flight operations core function.
      </p>

      <h3>Regulatory Compliance</h3>
      <p>
        Aviation regulations. Rest requirements. Training currency. Compliance enables continued flying.
      </p>

      <h3>Recurrent Training</h3>
      <p>
        Simulator sessions. Proficiency checks. Emergency procedures. Training maintains qualification.
      </p>

      <h3>Layovers</h3>
      <p>
        Time away from home. Hotel accommodations. Managing rest. Layovers part of lifestyle.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="career-considerations">
      <h2>Career Considerations</h2>

      <h3>Global Opportunities</h3>
      <p>
        Airlines worldwide hiring. Some regions with shortages. License portability considerations. Opportunities vary by region.
      </p>

      <h3>Career Paths</h3>
      <p>
        First officer to captain. Training captain. Check pilot. Management. Multiple paths available.
      </p>

      <h3>Seniority Systems</h3>
      <p>
        Airline seniority critical. Moving airlines resets seniority. Consider long-term. Seniority affects everything.
      </p>

      <h3>Lifestyle Impact</h3>
      <p>
        Time away from home. Irregular schedules. Family considerations. Lifestyle trade-offs real.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="faqs">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="space-y-6">
        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">I'm a pilot considering international work. What should I know?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            License validation varies by country. Airline benefits typically comprehensive. Medical certificate maintenance critical. Research specific airline and destination.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">Do international airlines provide good coverage?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            Major airlines typically yes. Benefits vary by airline and region. Verify specific terms. Gulf carriers often comprehensive.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">Should I get loss of license insurance?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            Strongly recommended. Career depends on medical. Separate from health insurance. Protection if grounded medically.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">What about radiation exposure at altitude?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            Real occupational hazard. Cumulative over career. Long-haul crews higher exposure. Consider in health planning.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">Is mental health coverage important for pilots?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            Yes but sensitive. Can affect medical certificate. Confidential support valuable. Industry improving approach.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">What's the career outlook for pilots?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            Strong long-term demand. Retirements creating openings. Regional variations exist. Generally positive outlook.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="next-steps">
      <h2>Next Steps</h2>
      <p>
        Start by understanding your target airline's benefits package and medical certificate requirements. Verify coverage supports maintaining flight fitness. Consider loss of license insurance separately. Research license validation for international positions.
      </p>
      <p>
        Pilots connect the world through aviation. Your coverage should support demanding flight careers—addressing circadian disruption, protecting medical certification, and ensuring your health across aviation positions worldwide.
      </p>
    </section>

    <CTABox
      title="Protect Your Aviation Career"
      description="Compare international health plans designed for Pilots working abroad across airlines, charter operations, and aviation organizations worldwide."
      buttonText="Compare Plans Now"
      buttonHref="/"
      variant="highlight"
    />

  </article>
</PageShell>
